247","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","about 1220":"circa 1220","Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland":"Atholl, Perthshire, Schotland","Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Caithness, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cupar Abbey, Fife, Scotland":"Cupar, Fife, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1192–1247":"about 1192–1247","1192–1247":"1192–1247","1192–Male":"1192–Deceased","1194–Male":"1194–Deceased","1195–Male":"1195–Deceased","1196–1244":"1196–1244","1220–1264":"1220–1264","1164–1210":"1164–1210","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","about 1192":"about 1192","6 Aug 1270 - crusades - plauge - at Carthage":"6 August 1270","before 1242":"before 1242","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","25 July 1210":"25 July 1210","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1247":"1247","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","about 1220":"about 1220","Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland":"Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland","Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom","Cupar Abbey, Fife, Scotland":"Cupar, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hastings","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Hastings (Sussex), near which the English army was defeated by the Normans in 1066. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣsta</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>. In the latter part of the 12th century, at the time of William the Lion, the surname was taken to Scotland, where it assimilated instances of the native Scottish surname <b>Harestane</b>.","English: variant of   Hasting   with Middle English genitival <i>-s</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hOistín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Oistín</i>’, the Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Augustine</i> (see   Austin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hasting","meanings":["English: from the Norman personal name <i>Hastang</i>, <i>Hastenc</i>, <i>Hasten</i> (Old Norse <i>Hásteinn</i> ‘high’ + ‘stone’). See also   Hastings  ."]},{"name":"Heston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Heston (Middlesex) or Histon (Cambridgeshire). The Middlesex placename derives from Old English <i>hǣs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Cambridgeshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hyse</i> ‘shoot, tendril’, also ‘son, youth’, + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish (Mayo): variant of   Hastings  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir David de Hastings VII Earl of Atholl was born about 1192, in Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, John de Hastings, was 30 and his mother, Elizabeth Capet, was 29. He married Forbhlaith Countess of Atholl before 1242. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1247, at the age of 56, and was buried in Cupar, Fife, Scotland."},"et":{"about 1192–1247":"umbes 1192–1247","1192–1247":"1192–1247","1192–Male":"1192–Surnud","1194–Male":"1194–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1196–1244":"1196–1244","1220–1264":"1220–1264","1164–1210":"1164–1210","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","about 1192":"umbes 1192","6 Aug 1270 - crusades - plauge - at Carthage":"6. august 1270","before 1242":"enne 1242","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","25 July 1210":"25. juuli 1210","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1247":"1247","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","about 1220":"umbes 1220","Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland":"Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland","Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Caithness, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Cupar Abbey, Fife, Scotland":"Cupar, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1192–1247":"noin 1192–1247","1192–1247":"1192–1247","1192–Male":"1192–Kuollut","1194–Male":"1194–Kuollut","1195–Male":"1195–Kuollut","1196–1244":"1196–1244","1220–1264":"1220–1264","1164–1210":"1164–1210","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","about 1192":"noin 1192","6 Aug 1270 - crusades - plauge - at Carthage":"6. elokuuta 1270","before 1242":"ennen vuotta 1242","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","25 July 1210":"25. heinäkuuta 1210","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1247":"1247","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","about 1220":"noin 1220","Atholl, 